featured_reviews.review_id:
Sunehri Masjid (literally 'Golden Mosque') is an 18th-century mosque in Old Delhi.  It was built by the Mughal nobleman Roshan-ud-Daula during the reign of the Mughal emperor Muhammad Shah.  It is located near Gurudwara Sis Ganj Sahib in Chandni Chowk, which was once a royal road leading to the Red Fort.
The Sunehri Masjid was built in the period 1721-1722 by the Mughal emir Roshan-ud-Daula, who was starting to rise to power in the court of the Mughal emperor Muhammad Shah.  The mosque was dedicated to Shah Bhik, the spiritual master of Roshan-ud-Daulah.
In 1739, the Persian Nadir Shah invaded Delhi.  Standing in the Sunehri Masjid, he ordered the looting of Delhi, which resulted in heavy casualties and extensive damage to the city.
The Golden Mosque, built on a platform above street level, can be reached by a flight of steps.  The mosque is topped by three bulbous, gilded domes and has slender minarets.  The front of the mosque has three arched entrances.  The interior of the mosque is divided into three sections.  Stucco decoration work in the form of arabesques and floral motifs is visible in both the interior and exterior of the mosque.

featured_reviews.review_id:
Sunehri Masjid, located in Old Delhi, is a stunning architectural gem that stands as a testament to India's rich cultural heritage. Constructed in the 18th century during the reign of Nawab Ahmad Shah Bahadur, this mosque captivates visitors with its grandeur and intricate design.

The mosque's name, "Sunehri," meaning "golden," aptly describes its beauty, with its golden-hued domes that shimmer under the sunlight. The three domes, adorned with intricate patterns and calligraphy, add a mesmerizing charm to the structure. The facade is adorned with ornate arches and floral motifs, showcasing exquisite craftsmanship from that era.

Stepping inside, one is greeted by a serene courtyard surrounded by arched corridors. The main prayer hall, adorned with beautiful pillars and decorated ceilings, evokes a sense of tranquility and spiritual sanctity. The symmetrical layout and attention to detail in the design reflect the architectural brilliance of that period.

Moreover, the mosque's historical significance adds depth to its allure. It has withstood the test of time, witnessing the passage of centuries while still maintaining its architectural integrity.

However, while the mosque stands as a testament to history, its maintenance and preservation need continuous attention to ensure its splendor endures for future generations to admire. Visitors should also be mindful of the local customs and dress modestly when visiting this revered place of worship.

In conclusion, Sunehri Masjid in Old Delhi is a captivating blend of history, architecture, and spirituality. Its intricate design and historical significance make it a must-visit for those interested in experiencing the rich cultural tapestry of India.

The mosque need some attention towards its maintanans and cleanliness.

featured_reviews.review_id:
The Sunehri Masjid, or Golden Mosque, was built in 1721-1722 by Roshan-ud-Daula, a Mughal amir. The mosque was dedicated to Roshan-ud-Daula's spiritual mentor, Shah Bhik. The mosque's name comes from its gilt-covered domes and peaks.
The mosque is located near Chandni Chowk in Old Delhi. It's still used for religious purposes.
The mosque's history includes:
In 1737, Nadir Shah displayed his unsheathed sword from the mosque's ramparts as a signal to commence the slaughter.
In 1739, the Persian Nadir Shah invaded Delhi.
The mosque's location has been coveted by numerous empires and dynasties, including the ancient ruler of the Kuru Empire and the British Raj.
There's also a Sunehri Masjid in Lahore. It was built in 1753 by Nawab Bukhari Khan, who was Lahore's deputy governor during the reign of Muhammad Shah.

featured_reviews.review_id:
Udham Bai later known as Qudsia Begum was first introduced as a dancer in Mughal Mughal court and soon she won everyone's heart including the 13th Mughal Emperor, Muhammad Shah. She was married to Muhammad Shah they both had a son Ahmad Shah Bahadur who became the 14th Mughal Emperor in 1748 after the death of his father. As a widow, she took the title, Qudsia Begum. She was an administrator and served as de facto regent of India from 1748 to 1754.

Qudsia Begum was known for her enthusiasm and keen interest in architecture best known for the palace and garden complex, Qudsia Bagh on the banks of Yamuna, although that one no longer exists.

In 1750-51, She constructed a mosque called Sunehri Masjid also known as The Golden Mosque for Nawab Bahadur Javed Khan, a chief eunuch of the royal household.

The Sunehri Masjid is located outside the Delhi Gate of the Red Fort, Delhi. It's a three-domed mosque, which was originally gilt with copper and other parts with a light salmon-colored stone from which it derives its name. The mosque has a main prayer hall and two tall tall minarets on the front and two small ones at the back. The elevated foundation upon which the mosque is based has a beautiful entrance gate.

In 1852, Bahadur Shah II repaired the mosque by replacing the damaged copper plates with sandstone.

featured_reviews.review_id:
Built in about 1561-2 CE, this relatively little-known mosque is one of the rare medieval buildings in Delhi that was built under the aegis of a woman: one of Akbar's wet nurses, Maham Anga, had it constructed. The name of the mosque 'Khair-ul-Manazil', means 'best of houses'. In the 16th century and till later, the mosque premises also housed a madarsa, of which you can still see ruined rows of double-storeyed cells surrounding the courtyard on two sides.

The large sehan or courtyard contains a shallow tank for wazu (ritual ablutions) and a now-closed well beside it. The mosque is still functional, so if you decide to go into the mosque (beyond the sehan), please take off footwear. There is a sign here to this effect.

The interior of the mosque is worth seeing: even though parts of the beautifully worked plaster and intricate coloured tile work has now disappeared, there's enough still left to make this very striking.

featured_reviews.review_id:
Khairul Manazil means the most auspicious of houses, is a historical masjid and madrasa built in 1561. The gateway of the masjid was made by red sandstone following Mughal architecture, but the inside structure of the building was made in Delhi Sultanate pattern. The mosque's design seamlessly blends traditional Islamic architecture with modern elements, creating a harmonious and inviting atmosphere. This structure was built by one of the most influential and powerful women of Akbar's court Maham Anga who was Emperor Akbar's wet nurse cum foster mother.

Currently the masjid is protected and maintained by the Archaeological Survey of India (ASI). Presently the building is under protection of Archaeological Survey of India.

featured_reviews.review_id:
Khairul Manzil or Khair-ul-Manazil meaning 'the most auspicious house' is a historic mosque built in 1561 in New Delhi, India.  The mosque is situated on the Mathura road to the south east of the Shershah Gate, opposite the Purana Qila.  The entrance gate of the mosque was built with red sandstone following the Mughal architecture, but the interior structure of the building was built in the Delhi Sultanate pattern.
This mosque was built by Maham Anga who was the foster mother of Emperor Akbar.  It is said that in 1564, Akbar was attacked by an assassin near the mosque while he was returning from the Nizamuddin Dargah.  Later it was used as a madrasa. Presently this building is under the protection of the Archaeological Survey of India.

featured_reviews.review_id:
Khair Ul Manzil means "the best of houses". Built around 1561 CE by Maham Anga, wet nurse of Mughal Emperor Akbar, this building originally included a Madrasa (Islamic School) along its courtyard which has mostly collapsed. The Mosque structure seems to be intact but in need of conservation. Tiny bits of the original Central Asian themed blue tile & mosaic work remains along the main arch of the mosque.
There is no parking but you can park opposite the road at the National Zoological Park. Everything is flat so persons of reduced mobility can easily walk in. Being a place of worship, do dress modestly, no shorts for men or short dresses for women & avoid going on a Friday as most worshippers would be there on that day.

featured_reviews.review_id: Tiada perintah Allah SWT yang seketat shalat. Ibadah ini wajib dilaksanakan setiap Muslim dalam kondisi apa pun, selama nyawa masih menyatu dalam raga. Tidak mampu berdiri, boleh sambil duduk. Tidak mampu sambil duduk, silakan sambil berbaring. Tidak heran, menurut hadis Nabi SAW, amal pertama yang akan dihisab di akhirat nanti adalah shalat. Jika shalatnya baik, tanpa cela, maka akan baik pula seluruh amal; jika shalatnya jelek, maka akan buruk pulalah seluruh amal.
featured_reviews.review_text: Tiada perintah Allah SWT yang seketat shalat. Ibadah ini wajib dilaksanakan setiap Muslim dalam kondisi apa pun, selama nyawa masih menyatu dalam raga. Tidak mampu berdiri, boleh sambil duduk. Tidak mampu sambil duduk, silakan sambil berbaring. Tidak heran, menurut hadis Nabi SAW, amal pertama yang akan dihisab di akhirat nanti adalah shalat. Jika shalatnya baik, tanpa cela, maka akan baik pula seluruh amal; jika shalatnya jelek, maka akan buruk pulalah seluruh amal.
featured_reviews.review_translated_text: There is no order of Allah SWT that is as strict as prayer. This worship must be performed by every Muslim in any condition, as long as the soul is still united in the body. Can't stand, can sit. Unable to sit, please lie down. No wonder, according to the hadith of the Prophet SAW, the first deed that will be counted in the afterlife is prayer. If the prayer is good, without fault, then all the deeds will be good; if the prayer is bad, then the whole deed will be bad.
